cmCourseInfo.recommendedPreparation: BIO130H1; CHM136H/CHM138H1/CHM151Y1; and 1 FCE from any of the following: MAT135H1, MAT136H1, MAT137Y1, MAT157Y1, PHY131H1, PHY132H, PHY151H1, PHY152H1

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

This is an online course. Lectures will be posted online (4-6 hours/week). Students will have the opportunity for synchronous online webinar class 1-2 hrs/week to ask questions and clarifications about lecture content (the sessions will be recorded). Students need the ability to view PDF files and must have access to Quercus (which includes access to Blackboard Collaborate). The assessment will take place during scheduled class time. The final in-person assessment will be announced by the Faculty of Registrar’s office.

Delivery Instructions

The lecture videos will be posted to watch asynchronously but help session & test will run synchronously. This means students have to ensure they are available Tuesday and Thursday 5-7 p.m. (Toronto Time).

cmCourseInfo.description:
"

An opportunity to go outside of the traditional university classroom and actively participate in a marine mammal autopsy. Learn the diversity and adaptive nature of marine mammalian physiology/anatomy as it compares to human. The course is 2 weeks (in May), one week of hands-on tissue dissection, and one week of group discussions of the findings and draft report preparation. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.

An additional fee is required to help cover the cost of delivery for this course. Please see https://physiology.utoronto.ca/psl378h1f for details.

"
cmCourseInfo.title: Field Physiology: Marine Mammal Autopsy
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: BIO270H1, BIO271H1/PSL201Y1/PSL280H1/PSL300H1, PSL301H1 or permission of the course coordinator

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

This is a two weeks intensive summer field course from May 16 - 27, 2022. Week one will be in-person at the University of Toronto, week two will be done virtually.   
Additional information and application may be obtained at http://www.physiology.utoronto.ca/psl378h1f. 
Space is limited and requires course director approval no later than April 1, 2022. Please note: an ancillary fee is required to help cover the cost of the delivery of this course addition to the university registration.  See http://www.physiology.utoronto.ca/psl378h1f for details.

Delivery Instructions

Week one will be in-person at the University of Toronto, week two will be delivered online synchronously.

courses.name: Comparative Marine Mammal Physiology in the Field

cmCourseInfo.description:
"

Hands-on monitoring of physiological measures with live dolphins, manatee and sea lions; field observations and applied learning to a physiology project. Two-weeks at the end of April early May: 1st week is spent at the marine research center in Mexico, 2nd week of wrap-up discussion and integration of data at U of T. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.

An additional fee is required to help cover the cost of delivery for the course. See https://physiology.utoronto.ca/psl379h for details.

"
cmCourseInfo.title: Comparative Marine Mammal Physiology in the Field

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

This is a two weeks intensive virtual summer field course from May 1 - 13, 2022.   
Additional information and application may be obtained in https://physiology.utoronto.ca/psl379h-virtual

Space is limited and requires course director approval no later than April 1, 2022. Please note: an ancillary fee is required to help cover the cost of the delivery of this course in addition to the university course fees. Fees for PSL379H online virtual course covers the personnel and the marine mammal facilities (trainers, staff and to record the in-water sessions).  Please see https://physiology.utoronto.ca/psl379h-virtual for details.

Delivery Instructions

The Department of Physiology will be offering a two weeks virtual ‘up close and personal videos’ with various species of dolphins & seals.  The first week is spend on BBcollaborate virtually visiting our marine mammals and the second week will be daily virtual class meetings to discuss individual projects, group discussion of the information learned and applied.
